s most important classics of Gulag literature. Ginzburg’s memoirs of her eighteen-year ordeal through Stalinist concentration camps, Journey into the Whirlwind and Within the Whirlwind, place her in the company of Russian writers, such as Alexander Solzhenitsyn and Varlam Shalamov. The contributors address Ginzburg’s Gulag experience through various vantage points, covering such topics as: memory, trauma, motherhood, love, survival strategies, and metafictional structures. The volume also provides a history of prison camp writings, capped with her biography, analysis of her correspondence with her son, Vasily Aksenov, and an interview with him.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAutobiographical memoryzSoviet Union. 0aInternment campszSoviet Union. 0aPolitical atrocitieszSoviet Union. 0aPolitical prisoners' writings, Russian. 0aWomen political prisonerszSoviet UnionxBiography. 7aHISTORY / Russia / Soviet Era.2bisacsh  aEvgenia Ginzburg, Gulag, women’s studies, Russian literature, memoir, history, twentieth century, prison camps, Journey into the Whirlwind, Within the Whirlwind.1 aArtwińska, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooke, Olga M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooke, Olga M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDuda, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeldt, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKolchevska, Natasha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomaromi, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKopelev, Lev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacKinnon, Elaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary